{
  "DNA replication is described as semiconservative because:": "",
  "Only one strand of DNA is ever replicated": "",
  "The replication process conserves energy by not using ATP": "",
  "Each new DNA molecule consists of one original (parent) strand and one newly synthesized strand": "",
  "Both strands of the original DNA are completely destroyed and rebuilt": "",
  "Semiconservative replication means each daughter DNA molecule contains one parental strand and one newly synthesized strand. This was experimentally demonstrated by Meselson and Stahl using nitrogen isotopes.": "",
  "Which enzyme unwinds the double helix at the replication fork?": "",
  "Primase": "",
  "Helicase": "",
  "DNA polymerase": "",
  "Ligase": "",
  "Helicase breaks the hydrogen bonds between complementary base pairs, unwinding and separating the two strands of the DNA double helix at the replication fork to provide single-stranded templates for replication.": "",
  "DNA polymerase synthesizes new DNA in which direction?": "",
  "3' to 5'": "",
  "From the center outward": "",
  "5' to 3'": "",
  "Both directions simultaneously": "",
  "DNA polymerase can only add nucleotides to the 3' hydroxyl end of a growing strand, so synthesis always proceeds in the 5' to 3' direction. This constraint leads to continuous and discontinuous synthesis on the leading and lagging strands.": "",
  "The lagging strand is synthesized discontinuously as short fragments called:": "",
  "Telomeric repeats": "",
  "Primer fragments": "",
  "Okazaki fragments": "",
  "Restriction fragments": "",
  "Okazaki fragments are short DNA sequences (100-200 nucleotides in eukaryotes) synthesized on the lagging strand. Because DNA polymerase works only 5' to 3' and the lagging strand runs 3' to 5' toward the fork, synthesis must occur in short segments away from the fork.": "",
  "Which enzyme joins Okazaki fragments together on the lagging strand?": "",
  "Topoisomerase": "",
  "DNA ligase": "",
  "DNA ligase catalyzes the formation of phosphodiester bonds between the 3' end of one Okazaki fragment and the 5' end of the next, sealing the gaps to create a continuous lagging strand.": "",
  "Why does DNA replication require an RNA primer?": "",
  "RNA primers serve as the template for the new strand": "",
  "RNA primers provide the energy needed for helicase to unwind DNA": "",
  "RNA primers protect the DNA from degradation by nucleases": "",
  "DNA polymerase cannot initiate synthesis de novo; it requires a free 3'-OH group provided by the RNA primer": "",
  "DNA polymerase can only add nucleotides to an existing 3'-OH group. Primase synthesizes a short RNA primer that provides this starting point; the primer is later replaced with DNA.": "",
  "The proofreading function of DNA polymerase corrects errors by:": "",
  "Sending a signal to halt all replication in the cell": "",
  "Removing the entire newly synthesized strand and starting over": "",
  "Using 3' to 5' exonuclease activity to remove incorrectly paired nucleotides": "",
  "Inserting a second incorrect nucleotide to balance the error": "",
  "DNA polymerase has a built-in 3' to 5' exonuclease activity that allows it to detect mismatched bases, remove them, and replace them with the correct nucleotide. This proofreading reduces the error rate to about 1 in 10 billion base pairs.": "",
  "Topoisomerase relieves torsional strain during replication by:": "",
  "Adding nucleotides to the leading strand": "",
  "Cutting, swiveling, and resealing DNA strands ahead of the replication fork": "",
  "Holding the separated strands apart": "",
  "Joining Okazaki fragments together": "",
  "As helicase unwinds DNA, it creates positive supercoils ahead of the replication fork. Topoisomerase relieves this tension by cutting one or both DNA strands, allowing them to rotate, and then resealing the break.": "",
  "Mismatch repair systems correct errors by:": "",
  "Removing the entire parental strand and replacing it": "",
  "Adding methyl groups to all bases to correct mismatches": "",
  "Reversing the direction of DNA polymerase": "",
  "Detecting and removing segments of the newly synthesized strand that contain mismatched bases, then resynthesizing the correct sequence": "",
  "Mismatch repair enzymes scan newly replicated DNA for base-pairing errors that escaped proofreading. They distinguish the new strand from the template strand, excise the region with the mismatch, and DNA polymerase fills the gap with the correct nucleotides.": "",
  "Telomerase is important because it:": "",
  "Synthesizes the RNA primers needed for replication": "",
  "Extends the telomeres at chromosome ends, preventing progressive shortening with each division": "",
  "Repairs double-strand DNA breaks": "",
  "Unwinds the DNA at origins of replication": "",
  "Telomerase is a reverse transcriptase that uses an RNA template to add repetitive DNA sequences to chromosome ends (telomeres). Without telomerase, telomeres shorten with each cell division, eventually leading to cell senescence.": "",
  "What is 'semiconservative replication'?": "",
  "A method of replication where one daughter molecule has both original strands and the other has two new strands": "",
  "Replication that conserves only half the nucleotides from the parent molecule": "",
  "The model of DNA replication in which each resulting double helix contains one original strand and one newly synthesized strand": "",
  "A type of replication that occurs only in prokaryotes": "",
  "Semiconservative replication describes how each parental DNA strand serves as a template for a new complementary strand, so each daughter molecule retains ('conserves') one of the original strands paired with one new strand.": "",
  "What is an 'origin of replication'?": "",
  "A protein that initiates RNA transcription": "",
  "The telomere region at each end of a chromosome": "",
  "A specific DNA sequence where the double helix is opened and replication begins": "",
  "The point where DNA polymerase falls off the template strand": "",
  "An origin of replication (ORI) is a specific sequence in the DNA where proteins bind to initiate the unwinding of the helix and the assembly of the replication machinery. Eukaryotic chromosomes have multiple origins to speed replication.": "",
  "What does 'replication fork' mean?": "",
  "The Y-shaped region of a replicating DNA molecule where the parental strands are being separated and new strands are being synthesized": "",
  "A fork-shaped enzyme that catalyzes DNA ligation": "",
  "The structure where RNA primers are stored before use": "",
  "A protein complex that holds two chromosomes together during meiosis": "",
  "The replication fork is the Y-shaped junction where the double-stranded DNA is unwound into two single strands, each serving as a template. Leading-strand and lagging-strand synthesis occur simultaneously at each fork.": "",
  "What is 'DNA ligase'?": "",
  "An enzyme that degrades damaged DNA, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these fragment dynamics operate": "",
  "An enzyme that synthesizes RNA primers, which is consistent with how fragment mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "An enzyme that unwinds the DNA double helix in most scenarios involving fragment factors": "",
  "An enzyme that catalyzes the formation of covalent phosphodiester bonds between adjacent DNA fragments, sealing nicks in the sugar-phosphate backbone": "",
  "DNA ligase joins breaks (nicks) in the DNA backbone by catalyzing the formation of a phosphodiester bond between the 3'-OH of one fragment and the 5'-phosphate of the adjacent fragment. It is essential for joining Okazaki fragments and completing DNA repair.": "",
  "What does 'proofreading' mean in the context of DNA replication?": "",
  "The process by which RNA polymerase checks mRNA for errors": "",
  "The checking of amino acid sequences during translation": "",
  "The ability of DNA polymerase to detect and remove incorrectly incorporated nucleotides using its exonuclease activity before continuing synthesis": "",
  "The verification of chromosome number after mitosis": "",
  "Proofreading is the 3' to 5' exonuclease activity of DNA polymerase that allows it to detect a mismatch immediately after nucleotide incorporation, excise the wrong base, and insert the correct one, greatly reducing replication errors.": "",
  "What is 'nucleotide excision repair'?": "",
  "The process of removing RNA primers from newly replicated DNA": "",
  "A repair mechanism that adds extra nucleotides to the ends of chromosomes": "",
  "The excision of entire genes that contain mutations": "",
  "A DNA repair pathway that removes a segment of the damaged strand containing a bulky lesion, then fills the gap using the undamaged strand as a template": "",
  "Nucleotide excision repair (NER) recognizes bulky DNA distortions (such as thymine dimers caused by UV light), cuts the damaged strand on both sides of the lesion, removes the segment, and uses DNA polymerase and ligase to fill the gap.": "",
  "What is a 'telomere'?": "",
  "The repetitive, non-coding DNA sequence at the ends of linear chromosomes that protects them from degradation and fusion": "",
  "The central region of a chromosome where sister chromatids are joined": "",
  "A segment of DNA that codes for ribosomal RNA": "",
  "A protein that holds the replication fork together": "",
  "Telomeres are repetitive sequences (TTAGGG in humans) at chromosome ends that form protective caps. They prevent chromosome deterioration and end-to-end fusion, and they shorten with each cell division unless maintained by telomerase.": "",
  "What does 'leading strand' mean?": "",
  "The strand of new DNA that is synthesized continuously in the 5' to 3' direction toward the replication fork": "",
  "The original template strand of the parent DNA molecule": "",
  "The strand of DNA that is synthesized discontinuously as Okazaki fragments": "",
  "The strand that is synthesized first during transcription": "",
  "The leading strand is synthesized continuously because its 5' to 3' direction of synthesis is the same as the direction of fork movement. It requires only a single RNA primer to begin synthesis.": "",
  "What does 'mismatch repair' mean?": "",
  "The correction of base-pairing errors that escaped DNA polymerase proofreading, by specialized enzymes that detect, excise, and replace the mismatched nucleotide on the new strand": "",
  "The correction of errors during RNA transcription, since the relevant base factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "Replacing damaged nucleotides with RNA nucleotides temporarily in most scenarios involving base factors": "",
  "The process of matching homologous chromosomes during meiosis, based on conventional assumptions about base": "",
  "Mismatch repair is a post-replication error correction system. Special proteins recognize base-pair mismatches, determine which strand is newly synthesized, excise the incorrect nucleotide(s), and DNA polymerase then fills the gap with the correct base.": "",
  "What is 'helicase'?": "",
  "An enzyme that unwinds the DNA double helix by breaking the hydrogen bonds between complementary base pairs at the replication fork": "",
  "A protein that holds the separated DNA strands apart": "",
  "An enzyme that adds telomeric repeats to chromosome ends": "",
  "An enzyme that synthesizes new DNA strands using a template": "",
  "Helicase is an ATP-dependent enzyme that travels along the DNA double helix, breaking the hydrogen bonds between base pairs and separating the two strands to create single-stranded templates at the replication fork.": "",
  "A geneticist studies a patient with xeroderma pigmentosum (XP), a condition in which the nucleotide excision repair pathway is defective. The patient develops severe sunburns and skin cancers with minimal UV exposure. Why is this repair pathway so critical for protection against UV damage?": "",
  "UV light causes single-strand breaks that only NER can fix": "",
  "UV light causes thymine dimers that distort the DNA helix, and NER is the primary pathway for removing these bulky lesions": "",
  "UV light prevents helicase from unwinding DNA, and NER activates helicase": "",
  "UV light destroys telomeres, and NER rebuilds them": "",
  "UV radiation causes adjacent thymine bases to form covalent dimers, which distort the DNA helix and block replication and transcription. Nucleotide excision repair specifically recognizes and removes these bulky lesions. Without NER, thymine dimers persist and cause mutations.": "",
  "A molecular biology student loads a gel with DNA samples from cells replicated in heavy nitrogen (15N) for many generations, then switched to light nitrogen (14N) medium for two rounds of replication. The student observes bands at the intermediate and light positions on the gel. This result is consistent with which model of replication?": "",
  "Dispersive replication": "",
  "Semiconservative replication": "",
  "Random replication": "",
  "Conservative replication": "",
  "This describes the Meselson-Stahl experiment. After two rounds of semiconservative replication in 14N medium, half the DNA molecules are intermediate density (one 15N strand + one 14N strand) and half are light (both 14N strands), which matches the observed gel pattern.": "",
  "A researcher finds that a bacterial strain has a mutation in its DNA polymerase that eliminates its 3' to 5' exonuclease activity but retains its polymerization ability. What consequence would this mutation have?": "",
  "DNA replication would stop completely": "",
  "The mutation rate would increase because the polymerase can no longer proofread misincorporated bases": "",
  "The DNA would become single-stranded permanently": "",
  "Okazaki fragments would no longer be joined together": "",
  "The 3' to 5' exonuclease activity is the proofreading function of DNA polymerase. Without it, misincorporated nucleotides are not detected and removed, leading to a much higher mutation rate during replication.": "",
  "Eukaryotic chromosomes have multiple origins of replication, while the typical bacterial chromosome has just one. Why is having multiple origins advantageous for eukaryotes?": "",
  "Eukaryotic genomes are much larger, so multiple origins allow replication to be completed in a reasonable time by initiating at many points simultaneously": "",
  "Multiple origins produce more accurate DNA copies": "",
  "Multiple origins eliminate the need for DNA ligase": "",
  "Multiple origins prevent the formation of Okazaki fragments": "",
  "Human cells have approximately 3 billion base pairs to replicate. With multiple origins of replication (tens of thousands), many replication forks operate simultaneously across each chromosome, allowing the entire genome to be copied within hours.": "",
  "A cancer biologist discovers that tumor cells express high levels of telomerase. She hypothesizes that inhibiting telomerase could be a therapeutic strategy. Why would telomerase inhibition specifically target cancer cells more than normal somatic cells?": "",
  "Most normal somatic cells have low or no telomerase activity, so they would be minimally affected, while cancer cells depend on telomerase to maintain unlimited replication": "",
  "Normal somatic cells also express high levels of telomerase, so both would be equally affected": "",
  "Telomerase inhibitors only enter cells with mutant p53": "",
  "Cancer cells do not have telomeres, so the drug has no target in normal cells": "",
  "Most normal somatic cells have very low telomerase activity and already undergo progressive telomere shortening. Cancer cells reactivate telomerase to maintain telomere length and achieve unlimited replication. Inhibiting telomerase would cause cancer cell telomeres to shorten and eventually trigger senescence or apoptosis.": "",
  "A student notices that on the lagging strand, DNA polymerase must repeatedly start and stop, creating many short fragments. Why can't the lagging strand be synthesized continuously like the leading strand?": "",
  "The lagging strand lacks a template, particularly when strand considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "DNA polymerase can only synthesize in the 5' to 3' direction, but the lagging strand template runs 5' to 3' toward the fork, so synthesis must proceed away from the fork in short segments": "",
  "Helicase only unwinds one strand at a time, which is consistent with how strand mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "The lagging strand has a different nucleotide composition because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "Because DNA polymerase can only add nucleotides in the 5' to 3' direction and the lagging strand template runs in the opposite direction relative to fork movement, synthesis on the lagging strand must occur in short segments (Okazaki fragments) moving away from the fork.": "",
  "A forensic scientist extracts DNA from a crime scene sample and needs millions of copies for analysis. She uses PCR (polymerase chain reaction), which mimics DNA replication in a test tube. Why must PCR include a heating step to approximately 95 degrees Celsius in each cycle?": "",
  "To repair any damaged DNA in the sample before amplification": "",
  "To activate the DNA ligase enzyme": "",
  "To destroy contaminating RNA in the sample": "",
  "To denature (separate) the double-stranded DNA into single strands so primers can bind and polymerase can synthesize new strands": "",
  "In vivo, helicase unwinds DNA. In PCR, heating to 95 degrees C serves the same purpose by breaking the hydrogen bonds between complementary strands, denaturing the double helix into single strands that can serve as templates in the next cycle.": "",
  "Lynch syndrome (hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer) is caused by inherited mutations in mismatch repair genes. Patients with this condition develop colorectal cancer at a much younger age than the general population. What is the molecular basis for this increased cancer risk?": "",
  "Mismatch repair genes normally prevent DNA from being replicated": "",
  "Mismatch repair mutations directly activate oncogenes": "",
  "Defective mismatch repair allows replication errors to persist, increasing the overall mutation rate and accelerating the accumulation of cancer-causing mutations": "",
  "The mutations cause telomeres to lengthen uncontrollably": "",
  "Defective mismatch repair means that base-pairing errors introduced during DNA replication are not corrected, leading to a 'mutator phenotype' with a dramatically elevated mutation rate. This accelerates the accumulation of mutations in oncogenes and tumor suppressors.": "",
  "A biochemist isolates single-stranded binding proteins (SSBs) and removes them from a replication system in vitro. Replication efficiency drops dramatically. What role do SSBs play that explains this result?": "",
  "SSBs stabilize the separated DNA strands at the replication fork, preventing them from re-annealing or forming secondary structures": "",
  "SSBs transport nucleotides to the replication fork": "",
  "SSBs are the primary enzymes that catalyze phosphodiester bond formation": "",
  "SSBs synthesize the RNA primers needed for DNA replication": "",
  "Single-stranded binding proteins coat the exposed single-stranded DNA after helicase separates the strands, preventing re-annealing and protecting the strands from nuclease degradation. Without SSBs, the template strands refold and become unavailable to DNA polymerase.": "",
  "During replication of a linear eukaryotic chromosome, the very end of the lagging strand cannot be fully replicated because there is no place to lay a new primer after the last Okazaki fragment. This is known as the 'end-replication problem.' How do germ cells and stem cells solve this problem?": "",
  "They express telomerase, which extends the telomeric DNA at chromosome ends, compensating for the sequences lost during each round of replication": "",
  "They replicate their DNA using RNA polymerase instead of DNA polymerase": "",
  "They skip replication of the last 100 base pairs": "",
  "They circularize their chromosomes before replication": "",
  "Telomerase, a reverse transcriptase with its own RNA template, adds repetitive telomeric sequences (TTAGGG in humans) to the 3' end of chromosomes. This extends the template so DNA polymerase can synthesize a complete lagging strand, preventing progressive shortening.": ""
}